entry.title: Rework computed rect() and xywh() values
entry.content:
rect() and xywh() should compute to inset() [1], but currently we only

do this when serialization the computed style. Instead actually compute

said shape functions to the equivalent inset() function.



Produce the canonical form as required for animations by building the

appropriate expressions.



Adjust Length::Add() and Length::SubtractFromOneHundredPercent() to

check the "explicit" flag(s) before potentially simplifying the

resulting expression.



This is behind the "XYWHAndRectComputedValue" flag, and when that flag

is removed it will be possible to prune the BasicShape class hierarchy

by removing BasicShapeRect and BasicShapeXYWH (plus supporting code).



[1] https://drafts.csswg.org/css-shapes/#basic-shape-computed-values

entry.title: Use the built-in Cronet telemetry stack
entry.content:
Before this CL, Cronet expected to be shipped with a CronetLoggerImpl

class that lives outside of Chromium:



- In the case of AOSP Cronet, that class would be built from AOSP along

with the rest of Cronet;

- In the case of Cronet embedded in Google 1P apps and Google Play

Services it would be built from an internal Google repo and the

resulting compiled class would be injected into the Cronet JAR at APK

build time;

- In any other cases (e.g. Maven) the class would not be present at

all.



The above setup is extremely contrived and requires maintaining an

API/ABI boundary across 3 different repos, making this code very painful

to maintain. We have to juggle between all these repos every time we

make any changes to telemetry atom schemas, which is something we expect

to do somewhat regularly in the future. This is not sustainable.



This CL simplifies the whole setup by making Cronet use the telemetry

code that was recently imported from AOSP into Chromium for this

purpose. From this point on, the entire telemetry logic lives in

Chromium and can be maintained just like the rest of Cronet code in the

normal way.



The AOSP and internal code that attempts to inject a CronetLoggerImpl

class will have no effect after this CL - that code will become dead and

we should clean it up as soon as this commit makes it to these repos.



The only downside of this change is that the atom definition still lives

elsewhere - the source of truth for that is in an internal Google

repo since the code that consumes the telemetry data is Google-internal.

The CronetStatsLog code is supposed to be autogenerated at build time

from the atom definition, but the relevant code generator only exists in

AOSP (under the name "stats-log-api-gen") and in the internal repo - it

does not exist in Chromium. So, for now, we'll have to run the code

generator manually and then manually copy its output over to Chromium,

every time we change atom definitions. This is not ideal, but that's a

small price to pay for the massive simplification that this CL brings.

Eventually we should solve this by having the atom proto definition in

Chromium (ideally autosynced from the internal repo) and then

autogenerate the logging code from it at build time in Chromium.

entry.title: Use some allowed C++20 library features in Autofill
entry.content:
Since Nov. 13, C++20 is allowed in Chromium! This CL replaces uses of

base::StartsWith() with std::string::starts_with() and uses of

base::EraseIf() with std::erase_if(). Both are among the allowed C++20

library features [1].



base::StartsWith() has an optional third parameter, defining whether the

comparison is done case-(in)sensitively. By default it's case-sensitive,

which is also what std::string::starts_with() does. For case-insensitive

comparisons, base::StartsWith() is kept.



std::erase_if() is only supported for std container. So usages for

base::flat_map/set/etc containers are kept.

Using std::erase_if() saves some includes, since the function is defined

in the header of the corresponding container (e.g. in ).



[1] https://chromium.googlesource.com/chromium/src/+/HEAD/styleguide/c++/c++-features.md#library-allowlist-20

entry.title: [passwords/desktop] Keep account storage opt-in when sync is disabled
entry.content:
This is an adapted revert of https://crrev.com/c/2261272. It changes

behavior in the following unlikely scenario.

1) User signs in

2) Opts into account storage

3) Turns on sync

4) Turns off sync

5) Signs in

Before this CL Chrome would not have access to account passwords in this

state. Now it does.



The motivation is to bring the behavior of the current opt-in pref

closer to the per-account SelectedTypes, which we want to migrate to.

In particular, it spares exposing a new SelectedTypes API similar to

OptOutOfAccountStorageAndClearSettingsForAccount().

Anyway, looking at the original CL and its linked bug, no one seems

convinced one behavior is much better than the other. Sync-the-feature

is also eventually going away, so this logic will disappear at some

point.

entry.title: Add user gesture checks to showPicker and fullscreen invoke actions
entry.content:
These were originally absent due to a faulty assumption.

If invokers only worked with trusted input then these checks

wouldn't be needed, but invokers also work with synthetic events.



As currently specced showPicker needs a user gesture check regardless.

Fullscreen actions aren't currently specced but adding gesture checks

matches the JS API equivalents, and removes a bypass for mitigations.

entry.title: working multiple organizations, invalidations, and udpates from tabs
entry.content:
TabData

- In order to support invalidating organizations when a tab is updated, the TabData now listens to and updates its observers when a meaningful navigation has occured.



TabOrganization

- The organization then listens to tab data changes, and marks itself as invalid, and notifies it's session.

- A fix was made to listen to TabDats that were passed in on construction.



TabRequest

- requests were completing before calling the response callbacks, this would lead to the session returning true for IsComplete before it actually was. To fix this the FAIL and COMPLETE states for the request were moved to after the response callback was called.



TabOrganizationSession

- Session now listens to its organizations and updates its observers when an organization updates.

- GetNextTabOrganization now takes organization validity into account. If a tab changes in an organization, it wont be displayed in the UI.



TabOrganizationService

- There was no way to reset a session from the TabSearchUI. ResetSessionFromBrowser now allows callers of the service to force a new session.



TwoTabsRequestFactory

- the two tabs request factory was updated to have 2 organizations for offline testing purposes.

> Introduce CompressionDictionaryTransportStoreTaskPriority FeatureParam

entry.title: Add all failing tests to deprecate-unload virtual suite.
entry.content:
This is a bit unorthodox. It adds 68 tests to the virtual suite and to

the NeverFixTests file. The alternative is that as we investigate each

test, we add it to VirtualTestSuites. This would require 68 CLs with

approval from OWNERS (and also dealing with merge conflicts in the

list of tests).



Doing it this way avoids that. I believe OWNERS are really only

concerned with making sure the virtual test suite is sane and are not

interested in the details of each specific test. It also gives us a

TODO list to work through as we move each test out of NeverFixTests.



Another altnerative was to check in a bunch of expectations files that

represent the current state of the tests in this virtual suite. I

don't like that because it would be checking in expectations that we

know are wrong and there's no way to distinguish which ones have been

investigated and which are just there so that I could land this CL.



One other orthogonal problem, the new-flaky-test detector is flagging these tests as flaky, even though they are marked "Skip". I have filed https://crbug.com/1502358 for this.



Adding `No-Try: true` to work around the broken flake detection.
